TY  - JOUR
T1  - Consequences of Abusive Supervision
AU  - Tepper, Bennett J.
Y1  - 2000/04/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/1556375
DO  - 10.5465/1556375
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 178
EP  - 190
VL  - 43
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Drawing on justice theory, the author examined the consequences of abusive supervisor behavior. As expected, subordinates who perceived their supervisors were more abusive were more likely to quit their jobs. For subordinates who remained with their jobs, abusive supervision was associated with lower job and life satisfaction, lower normative and affective commitment, and higher continuance commitment, conflict between work and family, and psychological distress. Organizational justice mediated most of these effects, and job mobility moderated some of the deleterious effects of abusive supervision.
AB  - Drawing on justice theory, the author examined the consequences of abusive supervisor behavior. As expected, subordinates who perceived their supervisors were more abusive were more likely to quit their jobs. For subordinates who remained with their jobs, abusive supervision was associated with lower job and life satisfaction, lower normative and affective commitment, and higher continuance commitment, conflict between work and family, and psychological distress. Organizational justice mediated most of these effects, and job mobility moderated some of the deleterious effects of abusive supervision.
